   =20
      Pipelines
   =20
 =20

The life of an investment banker is that you go around pitching a bunch of =
companies to try to work on deals for them. And some of those pitches event=
ually turn into assignments where you sign an engagement letter, do a deal =
for the company and get paid. So that=E2=80=99s the top (pitching) and the =
bottom (getting paid) of the funnel.
In between, there is ambiguity, and also most of the job. When you pitch a =
company=E2=80=99s chief financial officer on a deal, it is unusual for her =
to reply =E2=80=9CI love it, where do I sign?=E2=80=9D It is pretty common =
for her to reply =E2=80=9Cno, but thanks for coming in,=E2=80=9D but it is =
also common for her to reply something like =E2=80=9Chmm this is interestin=
g but could you do some more analysis on what the debt financing would look=
 like?=E2=80=9D You don=E2=80=99t shove an engagement letter at her=C2=A0at=
 that point. You go back and do the analysis. You send it to her. You call =
to follow up. You suggest some other analyses that you could run. You offer=
 to do all sorts of free work for her.=C2=A0You insinuate yourself into her=
 work and her decision-making=C2=A0so that=C2=A0when she=C2=A0does=C2=A0wan=
t to do a deal, she naturally chooses you to do it. A good investment banke=
r will be doing a lot of unpaid work for a lot of potential clients, becaus=
e that is the main way to generate paid work from those clients.
Another part of the job, though, is updating your bosses about what you are=
 working on and how likely it is to lead to fees. This is called a =E2=80=
=9Cpipeline report.=E2=80=9D Generally the subtext here is that if you are =
working on a lot of promising stuff, that=E2=80=99s good for your near-term=
 career prospects; if you are idle or working only on hopeless stuff, that=
=E2=80=99s bad. Certainly when I was an investment banker, my pipelines err=
ed on the side of optimism. If I was occasionally sending emails to a CFO s=
aying =E2=80=9Chey can I do some free work for you,=E2=80=9D and she was no=
t replying, well, that was a pretty promising lead, for me. Good enough to =
put on the pipeline report, anyway. Call it a 25% chance of a $5 million fe=
e?
Occasionally the incentives go the other way.=C2=A0Here is a Bloomberg News=
 story about how =E2=80=9CCantor Fitzgerald LP sued a firm launched by a gr=
oup of its former investment bankers, accusing them of stealing clients wor=
th millions of dollars in profit.=E2=80=9D Here=E2=80=99s the lawsuit, whic=
h claims that the bankers prepared for their departure by doing work for cl=
ients and=C2=A0not=C2=A0putting it in the pipeline:

They worked on several deals for=C2=A0months under verbal agreements with C=
antor clients, intentionally delaying the steps necessary to finalize a wri=
tten agreement between the clients and Cantor. The absence of executed cont=
racts for these matters eased the PEI Bankers=E2=80=99 ability to convince =
the clients to terminate their relationship with Cantor and immediately tra=
nsfer the matters to PEI after their departure.
The PEI Bankers omitted multiple matters on which they had verbal agreement=
s with clients from their =E2=80=9Cpipeline=E2=80=9D=C2=A0reports of pendin=
g engagements that were regularly disclosed to Cantor management, so as to =
hide the business opportunities that the PEI Bankers might take after they =
left.

This all makes sense but is incredibly alien to my own experience in bankin=
g.=C2=A0Not=C2=A0putting=C2=A0real=C2=A0deals in the pipeline, just wild.

