   =20
      Bid/ask
   =20
 =20

If you are a private tech startup and your valuation has gone down, three t=
hings are probably true:
=09Your valuation has gone down in a somewhat opaque way. It=E2=80=99s not =
like your stock traded on the stock exchange at $100 a year ago and at $50 =
today; your stock doesn=E2=80=99t trade on the stock exchange. Maybe there =
are some secondary transactions that are not quite representative, maybe Fi=
delity marked down its position, maybe you did a fundraising round at a 20%=
 lower price but with some structure=C2=A0that prevented the decline from b=
eing steeper. The decline in value is a bit fuzzy.=09Even assuming that you=
r latest market value is knowable,=C2=A0you=C2=A0probably think you=E2=80=
=99re worth more: You are an optimistic tech founder, you are changing the =
world, this is a temporary blip, you will do an initial public offering in =
a year or two at 10 times today=E2=80=99s obviously wrong valuation.=09Assu=
ming that your latest market value is knowable,=C2=A0prospective employees=
=C2=A0probably think you=E2=80=99re worth less: Tech startup employees want=
 to get on a rocket ship; they want stock worth $100 now that will be worth=
 $1,000 at your IPO. Declining stock values are bad; they suggest that ther=
e=E2=80=99s no rocket ship.

This makes it very hard to pay new employees in stock:=C2=A0You=C2=A0will b=
e miserable giving up stock at these low valuations, while the employees wo=
n=E2=80=99t be all that excited about getting it. The bid/ask spread is too=
 wide to strike a deal. The Financial Times reports:

Technology start-ups have slashed equity packages for new hires as they wea=
ther a prolonged downturn, according to new data from San Francisco-based s=
oftware company Carta.
People going to work at start-ups are receiving 37 per cent less equity in =
their companies on average compared with 18 months ago, the figures showed.=
=C2=A0Average salaries have barely changed during that time, shrinking by 0=
.2 per cent since November 2022. =E2=80=A6
=E2=80=9CCompanies are being very conservative in how they think about mana=
ging both cash and equity in an uncertain market,=E2=80=9D said Tom Keiser,=
 chief operating officer of Carta.
He said start-ups were holding back shares to help raise more funds once ma=
rket conditions improved, but added that workers had also contributed to th=
e shift in compensation.
=E2=80=9CAnother part of it is that employees no longer believe in trading =
hours or compensation for equity because they do not believe the market is =
there the way it was before to generate wealth,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9C=
HR departments are looking at what employees really value and they value ca=
sh more right now than they do equity.=E2=80=9D

When the stock is cheap, it is harder than ever for startups to part with i=
t, and easier than ever for employees to pass it up.

