   =20
      Factors
   =20
 =20

If you invest in stocks, your returns will come from roughly three sources:
=09The broad stock market goes up or down.=09You can get paid (or lose mone=
y) for taking on some particular systematic risk: Small companies=E2=80=99 =
stocks tend=C2=A0to outperform large stocks, and cheap stocks (by price-to-=
book value) tend to outperform expensive ones.=C2=A0=09You can be idiosyncr=
atically good at picking stocks.

The first thing is generally pretty easy to measure; there are widely used =
broad market indexes. The second thing is less obvious; someone needs to id=
entify the systematic factors and measure the data. The third thing =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0alpha, investing skill =E2=80=94=C2=A0is=C2=A0generally what=E2=80=
=99s left over after the first two things.
This means that identifying and measuring factors =E2=80=94=C2=A0Thing 2 =
=E2=80=94 is very important. For one thing, those factors are part of a pop=
ular investment approach: There are funds that try to capture factor premia=
 by, say, buying cheap stocks and avoiding expensive ones, and you want to =
know how well that strategy works. For another thing, lots of people=C2=A0r=
eally=C2=A0want to know how much investment skill their managers have =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0how much alpha they create =E2=80=94=C2=A0and since that is the=
 residue after subtracting factor returns, you need to know what those are.
For many academic and other uses, the main factor model is the Fama-French =
three-factor model, where the three factors are market returns, size (=E2=
=80=9Csmall minus big=E2=80=9D) and value (=E2=80=9Chigh minus low,=E2=80=
=9D that is, high book-to-price ratio minus low book-to-price ratio). And t=
he main source of historical data on the factors is Kenneth French=E2=80=99=
s website. And here is a fun Bloomberg Markets story by Mary Childs and Jus=
tina Lee about how sometimes that historical data =E2=80=A6=C2=A0changes?

In 2021, three professors then based at the University of Toronto noticed s=
omething strange and potentially unsettling. The numbers were =E2=80=9Cnois=
y=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 that is, they changed in significant ways depending on=
 when they were downloaded from the site. Pat Akey, Adriana Robertson and M=
ikhail Simutin wrote up their puzzling findings in two working papers. ...=
=C2=A0The authors noted that changes in the numbers seemed to improve the h=
istorical record of the value investment strategy=E2=80=94that is, of buyin=
g cheap stocks=E2=80=94and wrote that a =E2=80=9Clack of transparency=E2=80=
=9D made it impossible to know what to make of that.
Fama and French=E2=80=99s November article confirms that the numbers were c=
hanging and lays out the reasons. Among them: Corrections in historical sto=
ck market records and adjustments related to accounting rule changes that a=
ffected how some stocks are categorized. French=E2=80=99s Dartmouth website=
 now contains an archive of earlier versions of the data, so researchers ca=
n compare them.

=E2=80=9CEverything is seating charts,=E2=80=9D I sometimes say around here=
, about how informal networks of friendship and influence are often the mos=
t important incentives in business. In academia, I suppose the equivalent i=
s that everything is the acknowledgments section of working papers? After A=
key, Robertson and Simutin questioned the Fama-French data, Fama and French=
 circulated another paper explaining their methodology and the changes, and=
 they were mad:
Two days before the paper hit SSRN, a PDF of it landed in the email inboxes=
 of some of the country=E2=80=99s top economists and legal scholars. The ac=
companying message from Fama made it clear why he and French had written th=
e article=E2=80=94and also that he was annoyed. =E2=80=9CMost of you are in=
 the acknowledgements of=C2=A0two papers,=E2=80=9D he wrote. =E2=80=9CThere=
 is lots of strong language in those papers about the effects of updates in=
 the Fama-French factors. ... Our view is that their results are not surpri=
sing for those with experience in asset pricing research.=E2=80=9D Fama add=
ed: =E2=80=9CFor us, the whole experience is a great example of the old saw=
: No good deed goes unpunished.=E2=80=9D
=E2=80=9CMost of you are in the acknowledgements=E2=80=9D of critical paper=
s is I suppose how academics say =E2=80=9Ctraitors!=E2=80=9D

